In [[Canada]], [[statute]]s are one of the primary sources of [[law]]. A statute ends with housekeeping provisions, which are sections covering the details of the statute, such as the date of coming into force and the right of officials who administer the statute to make [[regulations]] under the statute.<ref>Margaret Kerr, JoAnn Kurtz, and Arlene Blatt, ''Legal Research: Step by Step'', 3rd Ed. Toronto, Emond Montgomery Publications Limited. 2010. Ch 2.</ref>

